We note that our presentation of the Wigner function will find utility representing any finite dimensional system within phase-space.
Early studies indicate that our approach is equally applicable to the generation of other phase-space distributions, such as the $Q$ function, and that the connections between them will be greatly elucidated by this approach. 
Furthermore, as construction of the kernel \ensuremath{{\ensuremath{\hat{\Delta}}\xspace}\left({\ensuremath{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}\xspace}\right)}\xspace recognises both the algebra and and ``parity'' of the underlying group structure believe we have a method to generate the Wigner functions needed to describe any system.  
For example, this formalism should help generate usable Wigner functions for high-spin $\SU{N}$ systems important in quantum gravity and other extensions to quantum mechanics.
Lastly, we see no reason why we could not extend our results further still and develop phase-space methods for more exotic frameworks such as string theory.

